Others have covered the ground well, but to summarize and simplify a
couple of points:

Antennas do not care about gauge. So concern yourself with that only to
the extent that strength is required. Similarly with insulation. Unless
actually shielded, a vinyl-insulated wire is no worse than a bare wire
which is no worse or better than magnet wire (varnished).

I jokingly follow what I call the 'left hand rule of mazes' when I set
up concealed antennas at home. We have a 117 year old house with
3-piece baseboards. So I can always skoonch the wire along the base
invisibly with a dull putty knife, also make it past, under or around
door moldings and so forth. If you have (as we do) three bedrooms and
five closets on our second floor (eschew wet locations for antennas as
a overly cautious safety choice), that is A LOT of perimeter. And the
third floor has two bedrooms and three closets, the ground floor even
more perimeter. So, start at a given point and keep turning 'left'
until you get back to your starting point. I used 24 ga enameled wire
on the second floor, something like 150' of it. From the antenna, I can
use a bit of insulated wire and either sand-and-solder a bit of a lead
to the concealed wire or just an alligator clip rubbed hard to grab
through the enamel.

If you have stretched carpet, it is easy to get a wire behind the
tackless and treat it similarly. As a cliff-dweller you already have
the elevation.

If you use _ANY_ sort of external or roof-mounted antenna, be sure to
install the proper lightning arrester and knife-switch to disconnect
the antenna when not in use. For the same reasons one does not run
antenna through wet locations.... overly cautious safety choice.

We also do have radiators, I use new-work ground clamps as needed to
get good grounds when required. The system is grounded at the boiler
and with a separate ground both to the rod and to the water service
(local code for gas-fired appliances). Just be careful if your have
similar systems that have been modernized. We have installed Runtal
radiators in place of some of the honking-big cast-iron units and as I
went from black iron to copper, I installed dielectric unions against
electrolysis. So those radiators and associated supply piping are not
good grounds.

Peter Wieck
Wyncote, PA
