I tend to think that an antenna in an apartment building, however
cleverly constructed, is going to offer disappointing performance in a
way that was not an issue 25 or so years ago. A modern dwelling has a
computer (maybe more than one), DVD player (ditto), cable or satellite
box, and other gadgets and gizmos that have high-frequency oscillators
and use switching power supplies that generate objectionable
interference on the shortwave bands.

It is fairly easy to control this situation in a single-family home, it
is impossible in an apartment building.

Before I spent any time putting wires under baseboards, I would do the
more basic test of whether reception is even possible among the RF
interference generated by all the other tenants' electronic activities.
