I find the telephone idea the most interesting -- in spite of the fact that
it's hardest to read.  It appears you set the telephone on a metal plate,
and connect the plate to the radio.  Interesting.

I recall my dad telling me that, a long time ago, he wanted to improve
reception on a table radio he had.  So he connected the antenna wire to the
telephone.  Radio reception was fantastic, but after a few days he noticed
he wasn't getting any phone calls.  When a friend told him he was trying to
get through, he called the phone company -- forgetting about the antenna.  A
technician stopped in, saw the radio connection, and told him that was the
problem.  He then said -- "If you want good radio reception, use THIS wire,
not that one."

Actually I'd be afraid to try any of them, as often the extra wires are used
elsewhere.  Plus, even with a capacitor, your radio could get a nice zap
when the telephone rings -- something like 90 volts, 25 Hz.  There's also no
telling what could be disrupted in terms of broadband internet or other
telephone add-ons.

Still, if you know for a fact that it's an unused wire, the telephone
connection through a cap might be a workable idea.

